{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496778"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:56:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:56:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1417"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1417","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1417"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.46,0.32,0.18,0.01,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1417"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103370"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1417","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1417"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1417"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85791"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"81"},{"type":"tags","id":"414"},{"type":"tags","id":"4535"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3811"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3817"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17458"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17469"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17481"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36654"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103370","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103370"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 55-year-old man, with a BMI of 29 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E, presents to his General Practitioner and has requested testing for diabetes because his brother was recently diagnosed with the disease. He has no other medical history and denies any symptoms. Apart from his body habitus, the physical examination is unremarkable. A number of investigations are ordered and they are all normal apart from a fasting blood glucose level of 7.5 mmol/L (3.9-5.5).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial action to take?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Repeat the fasting blood glucose level in a week\u0027s time","Arrange an oral glucose tolerance test (OGTT) in a week\u0027s time","Inform the patient that they have diabetes and provide lifestyle counselling","Referral to an endocrinologist","Inform the patient that they have diabetes and prescribe metformin"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EMany different tests are available to diagnosis diabetes mellitus including fasting BGL, non-fasting BGL, HbA1c % or OGTT. OGTT is generally only used in pregnant patients assessing for gestational diabetes. The cut offs for diabetes diagnoses include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFasting BGL \u0026gt; 7 (mmol/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENon-fasting BGL \u0026gt;11.1 (mmol/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHbA1c \u0026gt; 6.5%\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOGTT 2-hour \u0026gt;11.1 (mmol/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGenerally, to confirm a diagnosis in an asymptomatic patient requires two separate positive readings at least a week apart and \u003Cstrong\u003Ethe guidelines state that the second test needs to be the same as the initial test (e.g. 2x abnormal fasting BGL\u0027s or 2x abnormal HbA1c\u0027s).\u003C/strong\u003E In a symptomatic patient, only one test is required to make a diagnosis. Clinically present / symptomatic diabetes can include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELethargy\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPolyuria, polydipsia\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFrequent infections\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPoor wound healing\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWeight loss\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPoor wound healing\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EVision impairment / sensory loss\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAcanthosis nigricans\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERepeat the fasting blood glucose level in a week\u0027s time\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial action. A single elevated fasting blood glucose level is not sufficient to diagnose diabetes mellitus. Current guidelines recommend confirming the diagnosis with a second abnormal test result on a different day, especially in asymptomatic individuals. The guidelines recommend that to make a diagnosis the original test that is abnormal is the test that should be repeated, therefore another form of test for diabetes would not be recommended in this case. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EArrange an oral glucose tolerance test (OGTT) in a week\u0027s time i\u003C/strong\u003Es not necessary as the first step. While it can be used to diagnose diabetes, repeating the fasting blood glucose is a simpler and more direct method to confirm the initial finding. Furthermore, since the initial test conducted was a fasting blood glucose level test, the same test should be repeated the second time to avoid discordant testing results (one being positive and the other being negative), and this may occur due to different physiological measures of glycaemia between the differing tests.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInform the patient that they have diabetes and provide lifestyle counselling\u003C/strong\u003E is premature. A diagnosis of diabetes should not be made based on a single elevated fasting blood glucose level without confirmation from a second test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferral to an endocrinologist\u003C/strong\u003E is not warranted at this stage. The initial management of suspected diabetes, especially in an asymptomatic patient, can be handled by the General Practitioner until a diagnosis is confirmed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInform the patient that they have diabetes and prescribe metformin\u003C/strong\u003E is inappropriate without a confirmed diagnosis. Initiating pharmacotherapy should only occur after diabetes is definitively diagnosed, and lifestyle modifications are typically the first step in management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Asymptomatic raised blood glucose level requires two separate test results to diagnose diabetes mellitus."],"references":["The Royal Australian College of General Practitioners. Management of type 2 diabetes: A handbook for general practice. East Melbourne, Vic: RACGP, 2020. https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/clinical-guidelines/key-racgp-guidelines/view-all-racgp-guidelines/diabetes/defining-and-diagnosing-type-2-diabetes","Goyal R, Singhal M, Jialal I. Type 2 Diabetes. [Updated 2023 Jun 23]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK513253/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85791"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1417"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85791"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-21T19:23:45+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-21T19:25:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1417"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103370"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https:/